[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 8.10: Phenotype Extraction for Research
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research Infrastructure · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.08 per patient record set
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A researcher at an academic medical center has a hypothesis: patients with treatment-resistant depression who also have chronic inflammation markers (elevated CRP, IL-6) respond better to a specific adjunctive therapy. To test this hypothesis, they need a cohort of patients who meet three criteria: (1) diagnosed with major depressive disorder, (2) failed at least two adequate antidepressant trials, and (3) have documented inflammatory biomarkers above a specific threshold.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The EHR has structured diagnosis codes and lab values. Easy, right? Not even close.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The diagnosis code (F33.2, "Major depressive disorder, recurrent, severe without psychotic features") gets you a starting pool, but it misses patients coded differently (F32.2 for single episode, or even "adjustment disorder" in early documentation that was later reclassified). The "failed two adequate trials" criterion? That lives exclusively in free text. Progress notes, psychiatry consults, medication reconciliation narratives. A note might say "patient has not responded to adequate trials of sertraline 200mg and venlafaxine 225mg." Or it might say "tried two SSRIs without benefit." Or "Prozac didn't work. Effexor didn't work. Trying Wellbutrin now." Or it might be distributed across three separate visit notes spanning six months, each one mentioning a single failed medication.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This scenario is the norm in clinical research. The information you need to identify a study cohort is scattered across unstructured documentation, encoded in clinical shorthand, distributed across time, and expressed in a hundred different ways by a hundred different clinicians.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cost of doing this manually is staggering. Chart review (a human reading through every potentially qualifying patient's records) runs about 15-30 minutes per patient. For a study requiring 500 subjects from a pool of 50,000 candidates, that's potentially months of research coordinator time just to identify who qualifies. And the result is still inconsistent: different reviewers apply criteria differently, inter-rater reliability is often below 0.8 kappa, and the process is completely non-reproducible.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Phenotype extraction is the NLP-powered answer to this problem. It's the automated identification of patients who meet a complex clinical definition (a "phenotype") by analyzing both structured data and unstructured text in the EHR. When it works, it takes a process that took months of chart review and compresses it to hours of compute time, with complete reproducibility and explicit documentation of how every patient was classified.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m When it doesn't work (and this is the honest part), it fails silently. A missed negation means a patient who was ruled out for a condition gets classified as having it. An ambiguous temporal reference means a patient with a resolved historical condition gets flagged as currently meeting criteria. The research built on a contaminated cohort proceeds to publication, and nobody discovers the problem until a replication attempt fails.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The stakes are real. The difficulty is real. And the need is enormous: observational research, pragmatic trials, quality improvement, precision medicine cohort building, and biobank linkage all depend on reliable phenotype extraction from clinical text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Computational Phenotyping from Unstructured Text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Is Phenotype Extraction?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A clinical phenotype, in the research computing sense, is a computable definition of a patient characteristic. It's not just "does this patient have diabetes?" but a precise specification: "Type 2 diabetes, defined as two or more outpatient encounters with ICD-10 codes E11.x, OR one inpatient encounter with E11.x, OR HbA1c >= 6.5% on two measurements at least 90 days apart, OR documented treatment with metformin for glucose management (not PCOS), EXCLUDING patients with cystic fibrosis-related diabetes or steroid-induced hyperglycemia."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m That definition mixes structured data (codes, labs) with unstructured text requirements (confirming the metformin indication, excluding specific etiologies). The structured part is a database query. The unstructured part is an NLP problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Phenotype extraction is the NLP layer that resolves the unstructured text components of a phenotype definition. It transforms free-text clinical documentation into computable assertions: "this patient has documentation of failing two antidepressant trials," or "this patient's chest pain is described as non-cardiac in origin," or "this patient has family history of early-onset colorectal cancer."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The output feeds into a phenotype algorithm that combines structured and unstructured evidence to produce a final patient classification: phenotype-positive, phenotype-negative, or indeterminate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Components of a Phenotype Extraction Pipeline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Building a phenotype extraction system requires stacking several NLP capabilities together. None of them is individually new (most appear in earlier recipes in this chapter), but the combination and the precision requirements are what make phenotyping complex.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Named entity recognition (NER).** Identify clinical concepts in text: conditions, medications, procedures, lab values, symptoms. This is the foundation. If you can't find the relevant mentions, nothing downstream works. For phenotyping, you often need entities that go beyond standard medical NER: "adequate trial" (a qualitative assessment), "failed" or "non-response" (treatment outcome assertions), "family history of" (a framing modifier that changes who the entity applies to).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Assertion classification.** Every extracted entity needs an assertion status. Is this condition present, absent, possible, historical, or attributed to someone else (family history)? Recipe 8.8 covers this in depth. For phenotyping, assertion accuracy is critical: a negated condition ("no evidence of diabetes") getting classified as present creates a false positive in your cohort. At research-grade precision requirements (often 95%+ positive predictive value), even small assertion error rates become unacceptable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Attribute extraction.** Beyond recognizing that a medication is mentioned, you need its dose, duration, frequency, and route. Beyond recognizing a lab value, you need the numeric result and the reference range. Beyond recognizing a diagnosis, you need its severity, chronicity, and etiology. These attributes are what distinguish "tried sertraline" from "adequate trial of sertraline 200mg for 8 weeks."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Temporal anchoring.** When did this happen? Is the documented condition current or historical? Did the two antidepressant failures occur sequentially (required by the phenotype definition) or concurrently? Recipe 8.9 covers temporal extraction. For phenotyping, you need temporal reasoning sufficient to determine whether events meet the time-based criteria of the phenotype definition (e.g., "lab values at least 90 days apart").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Negation and context detection.** This overlaps with assertion classification but deserves its own mention because it's the single biggest source of phenotyping errors. "Patient denies chest pain." "No history of MI." "Father had colon cancer" (family, not patient). "Ruled out for pulmonary embolism." "Concern for possible lupus" (hedged, not confirmed). Each of these must be handled correctly, or the phenotype classification is wrong.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Section awareness.** The same phrase means different things in different note sections. "Diabetes" in the Problem List means the patient has it. "Diabetes" in the Family History section means a relative has it. "Diabetes" in the Assessment section might be "we are evaluating for diabetes" (not confirmed). Section-aware processing is non-negotiable for phenotyping accuracy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-document aggregation.** A phenotype is rarely determinable from a single note. You might need evidence from across the patient's longitudinal record: a diagnosis confirmed in one note, a medication trial documented in another, a lab value from a third encounter. The aggregation logic (how to combine evidence across documents) is where the phenotype algorithm lives, and it's where most of the domain expertise is encoded.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Phenotyping Is Hard (Beyond the NLP)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The NLP components above are table stakes. The real difficulty lives in the layers surrounding them:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Phenotype definitions are ambiguous.** Research protocols define inclusion criteria in clinical language, not computational language. "Adequate trial" of an antidepressant could mean different things: the APA says 4-6 weeks at therapeutic dose, but some researchers use 8 weeks, and "therapeutic dose" varies by medication. Your system needs these definitions operationalized into explicit rules, and different research teams might operationalize them differently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Gold standard annotation is expensive and contentious.** To train or validate a phenotype extraction system, you need gold-standard labels: patients who definitely meet the phenotype definition, and patients who definitely don't. Creating these labels requires clinician chart review, and clinicians disagree. Inter-annotator agreement for complex phenotypes is often kappa 0.7-0.85. When your annotators disagree on 15-30% of cases, what is "correct" becomes philosophically murky. Your system is being evaluated against an imperfect standard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Phenotype portability.** A phenotype algorithm developed at one institution may not work at another. Different EHR systems, different documentation styles, different provider populations, different patient demographics, different abbreviation conventions. "T2DM" is universal, but "NIDDM" (non-insulin-dependent diabetes mellitus, an older term) might appear in notes from a health system that still has clinicians trained in the 1980s. The eMERGE Network (a multi-site genomics consortium) has documented extensively how phenotype algorithms require site-specific tuning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prevalence and class imbalance.** For rare phenotypes (a specific genetic condition, a particular drug reaction), the vast majority of patients in your candidate pool won't qualify. If 0.5% of your candidates have the phenotype, even a 99% specific system will have a poor positive predictive value. The math is unforgiving for rare phenotypes, and the solution (higher precision at the cost of recall) means you miss real cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Reproducibility requirements.** Research demands reproducibility: another team should be able to take your phenotype algorithm, run it on their data, and get consistent results. This means every decision in the pipeline needs to be documented, deterministic, and versioned. Which NLP models were used? What thresholds were applied? How were conflicts resolved? What was the training data? Phenotyping is as much a data provenance problem as it is an NLP problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Is in 2026
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The landscape for computational phenotyping has matured significantly:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Standardized phenotype libraries.** The PheKB (Phenotype Knowledge Base) from eMERGE provides validated, published phenotype algorithms for hundreds of conditions. These are the reference implementations. They mix structured data queries with manual chart review criteria that are candidates for NLP automation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical NLP toolkits.** Apache cTAKES, MedSpaCy, and commercial clinical NLP services (including cloud-based offerings) provide the foundational entity extraction, negation detection, and assertion classification needed for phenotyping. None of them solve phenotyping end-to-end, but they provide the building blocks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Large language models.** LLMs can now perform zero-shot and few-shot phenotype classification with impressive accuracy on well-defined criteria. For simple phenotypes, you can often describe the criteria in a prompt and get reasonable patient-level classifications from clinical notes. The challenge is that "reasonable" (85-90% accuracy) isn't always "research-grade" (95%+ PPV), and the non-deterministic nature of LLM outputs creates reproducibility concerns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid approaches dominate.** The current best practice is a hybrid: rule-based extraction for structured and well-patterned data, ML-based NLP for unstructured text, and a deterministic combination algorithm that merges evidence using explicit, documented logic. This gives you the reproducibility of rules with the flexibility of ML.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At a conceptual level, phenotype extraction follows this pipeline:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Phenotype Definition] → [Criteria Decomposition] → [Per-Criterion Extraction] → [Evidence Aggregation] → [Classification] → [Validation]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Phenotype Definition:** The clinical specification of what you're looking for. Usually comes from a research protocol, published algorithm, or clinical expert.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Criteria Decomposition:** Break the definition into individual, independently evaluable criteria. Each criterion becomes a separate extraction target. Some resolve against structured data (ICD codes, lab values). Others require NLP against unstructured text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-Criterion Extraction:** For each text-based criterion, run the appropriate NLP pipeline: entity extraction, assertion classification, attribute extraction, temporal reasoning. The output is per-document evidence for or against each criterion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Evidence Aggregation:** Combine per-document evidence across the patient's longitudinal record. Apply aggregation rules: how many positive mentions are required? Does a single negation override multiple positives? How do you handle conflicting evidence across notes?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Classification:** Apply the phenotype algorithm logic to produce a final patient-level classification. Typically three classes: definite (meets all criteria with high confidence), probable (partial evidence), and excluded (evidence against).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Validation:** Compare automated classifications against manual chart review on a sample. Calculate positive predictive value, sensitivity, specificity. Iterate on extraction rules and thresholds until validation metrics meet research requirements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical for clinical NER and entity extraction.** Comprehend Medical provides out-of-the-box extraction of medical conditions, medications (with dose, frequency, route, duration), lab tests and values, procedures, and temporal expressions from clinical text. It handles negation detection and attribute linkage natively. For phenotyping, it provides the foundational entity extraction layer without requiring model training or clinical NLP infrastructure from scratch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for clinical document storage.** De-identified or appropriately consented clinical notes land in S3, organized by patient and encounter. S3 provides the data lake for the phenotyping pipeline, with encryption, access logging, and lifecycle policies for research data governance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** Phenotype extraction is a multi-step, per-patient pipeline with branching logic (different criteria may require different extraction approaches), error handling (a single note's processing failure shouldn't invalidate an entire patient), and checkpointing (you want to resume from where you left off, not start over). Step Functions provides visual workflow orchestration with built-in retry, error handling, and state management.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for per-document processing.** Each clinical note gets processed independently: extract entities, classify assertions, pull attributes. Lambda's pay-per-invocation model fits perfectly with the embarrassingly parallel nature of document-level NLP. Process 100,000 notes across 5,000 patients by fanning out to concurrent Lambda invocations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for evidence accumulation.** As per-document extraction results come in, they accumulate in DynamoDB keyed by patient ID and criterion. DynamoDB's fast writes and flexible schema handle the heterogeneous evidence payloads (medication attributes vs. lab values vs. diagnosis assertions all look different). The aggregation step queries by patient to pull all evidence for classification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for custom model hosting (optional).** If your phenotype requires extraction capabilities beyond what Comprehend Medical provides natively (e.g., a custom classifier for "treatment resistance" assertions, or a domain-specific entity type not in Comprehend Medical's ontology), SageMaker hosts the custom model behind an endpoint that Lambda calls as part of the pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Research Protocol] -->|Define| B[Phenotype Criteria\nDecomposition]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B --> C[Step Functions\nOrchestrator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Per Patient| D[S3\nClinical Notes Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Retrieve Notes| E[Lambda\nDocument Processor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Extract Entities| F[Comprehend Medical]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|Custom Models| G[SageMaker Endpoint\nOptional]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|Entities + Assertions| H[Lambda\nCriteria Evaluator]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     G -->|Custom Extractions| H
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Per-Doc Evidence| I[DynamoDB\nEvidence Store]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|After All Docs| J[Lambda\nAggregation + Classification]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     I -->|Query by Patient| J
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J -->|Classifications| K[S3\nResults + Audit Trail]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     K --> L[Validation Dashboard\nQuickSight]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style C fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend Medical, Amazon S3, AWS Step Functions, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon SageMaker (optional), Amazon QuickSight (optional) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehend:DetectEntitiesV2`, `comprehend:InferICD10CM`, `comprehend:InferRxNorm`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `states:StartExecution`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed. Even for de-identified data, BAA is required if any re-identification risk exists. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS with research-specific key; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; all API calls over TLS; Lambda environment variables encrypted |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, Comprehend Medical, and SageMaker. Private subnets only. No internet egress for PHI processing. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Full API logging. Research reproducibility requires knowing exactly what was processed, when, and with what configuration. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IRB Approval** | Institutional Review Board approval or waiver for use of clinical data in research. This is not an AWS requirement, it's an institutional and federal requirement. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Data Governance** | De-identification or consent framework per institutional policy. Limited data sets under data use agreements if sharing across institutions. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic clinical notes from tools like Synthea. MIMIC-III/MIMIC-IV discharge summaries (requires PhysioNet credentialed access). Never use real patient data in development. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical: ~$0.01 per 100 characters (entity detection). A typical 2000-character note = $0.20. Per patient with 40 notes = ~$8.00. At scale discounts and selective processing bring this down significantly. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | Extracts medical entities, assertions, attributes, and normalized codes from clinical notes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores clinical note corpus, intermediate results, and final classifications with full versioning |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the multi-step per-patient pipeline with error handling and checkpointing |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Per-document entity extraction, criteria evaluation, and patient-level aggregation |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Accumulates per-criterion evidence across documents for each patient |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for all data stores and processing |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Logging, metrics, and alerts for pipeline health and throughput |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts custom NLP models for phenotype-specific extraction (optional) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Decompose the phenotype into computable criteria.** Before any NLP happens, you need to translate the clinical phenotype definition into a set of criteria that can each be independently evaluated. This is the most intellectually demanding step and requires close collaboration between the research team and the engineering team. Each criterion must specify: what entity types to look for, what assertion states are acceptable (present only? or present + possible?), what attributes are required (dose thresholds, temporal constraints), and how much evidence constitutes a positive finding. This decomposition is configuration, not code, but it drives everything downstream. Skip this step or do it carelessly, and your entire pipeline produces meaningless results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "phenotype_id": "treatment_resistant_depression_v2",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "phenotype_name": "Treatment-Resistant Depression with Inflammatory Markers",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "version": "2.1",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "criteria": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "criterion_id": "C1_MDD_DIAGNOSIS",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "description": "Major Depressive Disorder diagnosis",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "type": "structured_or_text",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "structured_query": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "icd10_codes": ["F32.0", "F32.1", "F32.2", "F32.9", "F33.0", "F33.1", "F33.2", "F33.9"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "min_occurrences": 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "context": "outpatient_or_inpatient"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "text_criteria": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "target_entities": ["MEDICAL_CONDITION"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "terms": ["major depressive disorder", "major depression", "MDD", "recurrent depression"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "required_assertion": "POSITIVE",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "exclude_sections": ["FAMILY_HISTORY", "SOCIAL_HISTORY"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "evidence_threshold": "structured_sufficient_alone_OR_text_2_plus_mentions"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "criterion_id": "C2_TREATMENT_FAILURE",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "description": "Failed at least 2 adequate antidepressant trials",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "type": "text_required",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "text_criteria": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "target_entities": ["MEDICATION"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "medication_categories": ["SSRI", "SNRI", "TCA", "MAOI", "atypical_antidepressant"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "required_attributes": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m           "treatment_outcome": ["failed", "non-response", "inadequate response", "did not respond", "ineffective", "not helpful"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m           "adequacy_indicators": ["adequate trial", "therapeutic dose", "full dose", "maximum dose"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "min_distinct_medications": 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "temporal_constraint": "sequential_not_concurrent"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "evidence_threshold": "2_distinct_medications_with_failure_assertion"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "criterion_id": "C3_INFLAMMATORY_MARKERS",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "description": "Elevated inflammatory biomarkers",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "type": "structured_preferred",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "structured_query": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "lab_tests": ["CRP", "hs-CRP", "IL-6", "ESR"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "threshold": {"CRP": ">3.0 mg/L", "hs-CRP": ">3.0 mg/L", "IL-6": ">7 pg/mL", "ESR": ">20 mm/hr"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "min_occurrences": 1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "text_criteria": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "target_entities": ["TEST_TREATMENT_PROCEDURE", "TEST_VALUE"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "terms": ["elevated CRP", "elevated inflammatory markers", "high CRP", "inflammation"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "required_assertion": "POSITIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       "evidence_threshold": "structured_lab_value_preferred_text_confirmatory_only"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "classification_logic": "ALL_criteria_must_be_met",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "output_classes": ["DEFINITE", "PROBABLE", "EXCLUDED", "INSUFFICIENT_DATA"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Process each clinical note through entity extraction.** For every note in the patient's record, send it through Comprehend Medical to pull out medical entities with their assertions, attributes, and normalized codes. The key insight here is that you're not processing the note generically: you're processing it with your phenotype criteria in mind. Not every entity in the note matters. A phenotype for depression doesn't care about the patient's knee replacement (usually). But you extract everything at the document level because filtering happens in the next step, and you don't want to re-process notes if you add criteria later. Think of this as building an evidence index for the patient's record.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION process_note(patient_id, note_id, note_text, note_metadata):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Send the clinical note to Comprehend Medical for entity extraction.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // DetectEntitiesV2 returns medical conditions, medications, tests, procedures,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // anatomy mentions, and temporal expressions, each with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Text span (what was found)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Category (MEDICAL_CONDITION, MEDICATION, TEST_TREATMENT_PROCEDURE, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Type (more specific: DX_NAME, GENERIC_NAME, TEST_NAME, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Traits (NEGATION, DIAGNOSIS, SIGN, SYMPTOM, etc.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Attributes (linked properties like dosage, frequency, test value)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //   - Score (confidence 0.0 to 1.0)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     entities = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntitiesV2(Text = note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Also run specialized detections for medications and diagnoses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // to get normalized codes (RxNorm CUIs, ICD-10 codes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     rx_entities = call ComprehendMedical.InferRxNorm(Text = note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     icd_entities = call ComprehendMedical.InferICD10CM(Text = note_text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Determine assertion status for each entity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Comprehend Medical provides "Traits" including NEGATION.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // An entity with NEGATION trait = "absent" assertion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // No NEGATION trait = "present" (with caveats for hypothetical language).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     processed_entities = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each entity in entities.Entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         assertion = "POSITIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity has trait NEGATION:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assertion = "NEGATIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity has trait HYPOTHETICAL:  // Not all services provide this natively
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assertion = "HYPOTHETICAL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Capture the note section context if available from note_metadata.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Section information helps exclude family history mentions, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         section = determine_section(entity.BeginOffset, note_metadata.section_boundaries)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         processed_entity = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             text:        entity.Text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             category:    entity.Category,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             type:        entity.Type,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             assertion:   assertion,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence:  entity.Score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             attributes:  entity.Attributes,   // dose, frequency, route, test values
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             section:     section,              // HPI, PMH, FAMILY_HISTORY, MEDICATIONS, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             note_id:     note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             note_date:   note_metadata.date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             offsets:     [entity.BeginOffset, entity.EndOffset]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append processed_entity to processed_entities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Merge in normalized medication and diagnosis codes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     processed_entities = enrich_with_normalized_codes(processed_entities, rx_entities, icd_entities)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:  patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         note_id:     note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         note_date:   note_metadata.date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         entities:    processed_entities
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Evaluate each note against phenotype criteria.** Now take the extracted entities and check which phenotype criteria they provide evidence for. This is the matching step: does this entity, with this assertion, in this section, with these attributes, count as evidence for criterion C1, C2, or C3? The matching rules come directly from the phenotype definition in Step 1. A medication entity matching "sertraline" with a "failure" attribute contributes to criterion C2. A medical condition entity matching "major depressive disorder" with a positive assertion in the HPI section contributes to criterion C1.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION evaluate_against_criteria(extraction_result, phenotype_definition):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For each criterion in the phenotype definition,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // check if this note's entities provide evidence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     evidence_items = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each criterion in phenotype_definition.criteria:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF criterion.type == "text_required" OR criterion.type == "structured_or_text":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Filter entities to those relevant to this criterion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             relevant_entities = filter_entities(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 extraction_result.entities,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 target_categories = criterion.text_criteria.target_entities,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 target_terms      = criterion.text_criteria.terms,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 required_assertion = criterion.text_criteria.required_assertion,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 exclude_sections  = criterion.text_criteria.exclude_sections
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             FOR each matched_entity in relevant_entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // Check if additional attributes are required
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 attribute_match = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF criterion.text_criteria has required_attributes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     attribute_match = check_attributes(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         matched_entity,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         criterion.text_criteria.required_attributes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 IF attribute_match AND matched_entity.confidence >= 0.80:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     evidence_item = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         criterion_id:  criterion.criterion_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         patient_id:    extraction_result.patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         note_id:       extraction_result.note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         note_date:     extraction_result.note_date,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         entity_text:   matched_entity.text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         assertion:     matched_entity.assertion,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         confidence:    matched_entity.confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         section:       matched_entity.section,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         attributes:    matched_entity.attributes,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                         evidence_type: "NLP_EXTRACTION"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     append evidence_item to evidence_items
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN evidence_items
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION filter_entities(entities, target_categories, target_terms, required_assertion, exclude_sections):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Match entities based on category, terminology, assertion, and section
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     matched = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each entity in entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Category must match (e.g., MEDICAL_CONDITION, MEDICATION)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity.category NOT IN target_categories:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Section must not be excluded (e.g., skip FAMILY_HISTORY for patient conditions)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity.section IN exclude_sections:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Assertion must match the requirement
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF required_assertion == "POSITIVE" AND entity.assertion != "POSITIVE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Term matching: does the entity text match any of the target terms?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Use case-insensitive substring or normalized code matching
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF entity.text (normalized, lowercase) matches any term in target_terms:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append entity to matched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF entity has normalized_code matching any target code:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append entity to matched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN matched
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Aggregate evidence across all notes for each patient.** A single note rarely provides enough evidence to classify a patient. This step pulls together all the evidence accumulated across the patient's entire note corpus and organizes it by criterion. For criterion C2 (treatment failures), it counts distinct medications with failure assertions. For criterion C1 (MDD diagnosis), it counts the number of positive mentions across different encounters. The aggregation logic is criterion-specific because different criteria have different evidence thresholds.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION aggregate_patient_evidence(patient_id, phenotype_definition):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Query DynamoDB for all evidence items for this patient
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_evidence = query DynamoDB where patient_id = patient_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Group evidence by criterion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     evidence_by_criterion = group all_evidence by criterion_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Evaluate each criterion's evidence against its threshold
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     criterion_results = empty map
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each criterion in phenotype_definition.criteria:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         criterion_evidence = evidence_by_criterion[criterion.criterion_id] or empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Apply criterion-specific aggregation logic
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF criterion.criterion_id == "C2_TREATMENT_FAILURE":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Special aggregation: count DISTINCT medications with failure assertions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             distinct_failed_meds = extract unique medication names from criterion_evidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                     where evidence indicates treatment failure
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             criterion_results[criterion.criterion_id] = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 met:              length(distinct_failed_meds) >= criterion.text_criteria.min_distinct_medications,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence:       average confidence of supporting evidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 evidence_count:   length(criterion_evidence),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 distinct_items:   distinct_failed_meds,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 supporting_notes: list of note_ids providing evidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Standard aggregation: count positive evidence instances
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             positive_evidence = filter criterion_evidence where assertion == "POSITIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Apply evidence threshold from phenotype definition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             threshold_met = evaluate_threshold(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 criterion.evidence_threshold,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 positive_evidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             criterion_results[criterion.criterion_id] = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 met:              threshold_met,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence:       average confidence of positive_evidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 evidence_count:   length(positive_evidence),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 supporting_notes: list of note_ids from positive_evidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN criterion_results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Classify the patient.** Apply the phenotype algorithm's classification logic to the aggregated criterion results. If all criteria are met with high confidence, the patient is "DEFINITE." If some criteria are met but others have only partial evidence, the patient is "PROBABLE." If any criterion has definitive negative evidence, the patient is "EXCLUDED." If there simply isn't enough documentation to make a determination, the patient is "INSUFFICIENT_DATA." This final classification, along with all supporting evidence, becomes the output of the pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_patient(patient_id, criterion_results, phenotype_definition):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Apply classification logic from phenotype definition
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_met = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     any_excluded = FALSE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     partial_evidence = FALSE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each criterion_id, result in criterion_results:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF result.met == FALSE AND result.evidence_count == 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // No evidence at all for this criterion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             all_met = FALSE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             partial_evidence = FALSE  // Can't even call it partial
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF result.met == FALSE AND result.evidence_count > 0:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Some evidence exists but doesn't meet threshold
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             all_met = FALSE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             partial_evidence = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE IF result.met == TRUE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Criterion satisfied
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check for exclusion evidence (negative assertions on inclusion criteria)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For example: "Patient does NOT have depression" directly contradicts C1
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     exclusion_evidence = check_exclusion_criteria(patient_id, phenotype_definition)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF exclusion_evidence is not empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         any_excluded = TRUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Determine final classification
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF any_excluded:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classification = "EXCLUDED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF all_met AND minimum_confidence(criterion_results) >= 0.85:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classification = "DEFINITE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF all_met AND minimum_confidence(criterion_results) < 0.85:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classification = "PROBABLE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE IF partial_evidence:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classification = "PROBABLE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classification = "INSUFFICIENT_DATA"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build the complete output record
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         patient_id:        patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phenotype_id:      phenotype_definition.phenotype_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         phenotype_version: phenotype_definition.version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classification:    classification,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         criteria_results:  criterion_results,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         exclusion_evidence: exclusion_evidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         processing_timestamp: current UTC timestamp,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         notes_processed:   count of unique note_ids across all evidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         pipeline_version:  "1.0.3"  // version of the processing code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Write to final results store
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     store result in S3 results bucket as JSON
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN result
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
